english:
  title: Three Memorials of Remonstrance
  author: Kim Bu-sik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A creature as humble as the ant ventures forth with sincere heart, yet Heaven's vast compassion has not yet inclined toward pity. Repeatedly you have issued your sovereign's extraordinary decree and shown your magnanimous care most abundantly. This worthless person knows not what to do with such grace.

    My nature has been dull and clouded from birth, my learning shallow and narrow. In seeking sustenance, I was driven only by hunger and cold, never daring to dream of wealth and status. Yet by fortunate circumstance, I have undeservedly received your favor and served in high and glorious positions. Given charge of the great wheel of state, I confess I possess no other talent. Receiving command in matters of war, who could claim that greater numbers alone ensure greater success? Day and night I have labored without respite, rushing between court and field, yet I have accomplished nothing worthy of even a hair's breadth, while receiving blessings vast as mountains. This is the nature of things—when fullness becomes excessive, it cannot be sustained; when fortune reaches its zenith, calamity must follow. How could I not heed this warning? Now heaven and earth are thrown into discord, customs decay, and our people suffer in poverty and dispersion. Whose fault is this? Our enemies grow bold and ungovernable. Surely we must prepare against them. The nation's fate hangs in the balance; the burden falls upon those in high office. Yet I bring no wise counsel to the throne, no benefit to the common folk. If judgment be rendered, punishment would be just. How could reward be deserved? Besides, such elevated rank and rare favor are not what my honest heart desires, nor do my past deeds warrant them. Therefore I lay bare my heart and firmly decline, again and again, without ceasing. I humbly implore your compassion for this foolish sincerity, and beg that you grant your assent. Then the frog in the well may find rest in the crumbling stone, and the bird of the river need not be dazed by the sight of great offerings. My humble petition hopes only for this.
  footnotes:
    - Kim Bu-sik (1075-1151) was a prominent Goryeo statesman and historian. This is a memorial declining high office, written in the formal style of court remonstrance.
    - 'The three sections of the memorial follow the traditional form: an opening declaration of purpose, the main body of argument, and a concluding petition.'
    - The imagery of the frog in the well and the bird of the river derives from Buddhist and Daoist philosophy, representing the speaker's desire to return to humble simplicity rather than remain in high position.
